04425nam a22006975i 9780801463532DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014635327 a10.7591/97808014635322doi  a(DE-B1597)515024  a(OCoLC)1083582038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aDC192b.J35 2008eb 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a944.042221 aJainchill, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReimagining Politics after the Terror :bThe Republican Origins of French Liberalism /cAndrew Jainchill. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Translations and Abbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Constitution of the Year III -- t2. The Post-Terror Discourse of Moeurs -- t3. Liberal Republicanism during the Directory 108 -- t4. A Republican Empire? Debate on Expansion, 1794-99 -- t5. Liberal Authoritarianism and the Constitution of the Year VIII -- t6. Liberal Republicanism and Dissent against Bonaparte -- tEpilogue: The Fate of French Liberal Republicanism -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the wake of the Terror, France's political and intellectual elites set out to refound the Republic and, in so doing, reimagined the nature of the political order. They argued vigorously over imperial expansion, constitutional power, personal liberty, and public morality. In Reimagining Politics after the Terror, Andrew Jainchill rewrites the history of the origins of French Liberalism by telling the story of France's underappreciated "republican moment" during the tumultuous years between 1794 and Napoleon's declaration of a new French Empire in 1804.Examining a wide range of political and theoretical debates, Jainchill offers a compelling reinterpretation of the political culture of post-Terror France and of the establishment of Napoleon's Consulate. He also provides new readings of works by the key architects of early French Liberalism, including Germaine de Staël, Benjamin Constant, and, in the epilogue, Alexis de Tocqueville. The political culture of the post-Terror period was decisively shaped by the classical republican tradition of the early modern Atlantic world and, as Jainchill persuasively argues, constituted France's "Machiavellian Moment." Out of this moment, a distinctly French version of liberalism began to take shape. Reimagining Politics after the Terror is essential reading for anyone concerned with the history of political thought, the origins and nature of French Liberalism, and the end of the French Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aLiberalismzFrancexHistory. 0aPolitical culturezFrancexHistory. 0aRepublicanismzFrancexHistory. 4aEurope. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146353240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801463532423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801463532.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK